'''Michael Robert "Mickey" Morandini''' (born April 22, 1966, in [[Kittanning, Pennsylvania]]) is a former [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] [[second baseman]] who played for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], [[Chicago Cubs]], and [[Toronto Blue Jays]] of [[Major League Baseball]], and the current manager of the A-level [[Williamsport Crosscutters]]. He played in the [[1993 World Series]] as a member of the Phillies, and the [[1998 National League Division Series]] as a member of the Cubs.

==Early life and career==
Morandini grew up in the [[Pittsburgh]] suburb of [[Leechburg, Pennsylvania]], where he attended [[Leechburg Area High School]].<ref name="cube">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/M/Mickey-Morandini.shtml|title=Mickey Morandini|publisher=The Baseball Cube|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> After graduation, Morandini attended [[Indiana University]], where he started his college career as a [[center fielder]], moving to the infield as a [[third baseman]] and [[shortstop]] after his freshman year.<ref name="big10">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/080608aaa.html|title=Olympic Spotlight: Baseball's Mickey Morandini, Jim Abbott, and Clayton Richard|last=Smith|first=Jeff|date=2008-08-06|work=BigTen.org|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> Morandini declined the option to enter the [[Major League Baseball draft]] in 1987, citing his desire to play for the [[United States national baseball team|United States national team]] in the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]].<ref name="big10"/> After appearing in one game during the Olympics, he returned to Indiana for his senior season; he was named a second-team [[All-American]] for the 1988 season. Morandini graduated as the Indiana University record-holder in several statistical categories, including [[runs scored]] (277), [[double (baseball)|doubles]] (61), [[triple (baseball)|triples]] (29), and [[stolen bases]] (127).<ref name="big10"/> The [[Philadelphia Phillies]] selected Morandini in the fifth round of the [[1988 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?query_type=year_round&year_ID=1988&draft_round=5&draft_type=junreg|title=Amateur Draft: 5th Round of the 1988 June Draft|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref>

===Minor leagues===
After being drafted, the Phillies assigned Morandini to the [[Spartanburg Phillies]], one of their [[Minor league baseball#Class A|A-level]] [[List of Philadelphia Phillies minor league affiliates|affiliates]] in [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]]. He played in 63 games for Spartanburg in 1989, batting .338 with 19 doubles, earning him a promotion to the high-A [[Clearwater Phillies]].<ref name="brefminors">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=morand001mic|title=Mickey Morandini Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> In Florida, he notched 19 [[hit (baseball)|hits]] and 14 runs scored in 63 at-bats; he also [[Run batted in|batted in]] four runs.<ref name="cube"/> Finishing the season with the [[Minor league baseball#Double-A|AA-level]] [[Reading Phillies]], Morandini hit 5 home runs in 188 at-bats, posting a .351 average.<ref name="brefminors"/> Morandini won the 1989 Paul Owens Award as the top minor league position player in the Phillies organization. Morandini committed 22 [[error (baseball)|errors]] in his first professional season as a shortstop and with [[Dickie Thon]] playing shortstop at the major league level, the Phillies organization shifted him to his eventual major league position, [[second baseman|second base]] during the 1989 Florida Instructional league season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Phils used instructional league to experiment |author=Mike Payne |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=1989-11-06 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6dMNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UHgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4736,590536&dq=phillies+paul-owens-award&hl=en}}</ref>

Morandini spent the majority of the 1990 season with the [[Triple-A (baseball)|AAA]] [[Scranton/Wilkes-Barre Red Barons]]. While playing in 139 games, he stole 16 bases and batted in 31 runs in 503 at-bats. He also batted .260 and scored 76 runs.<ref name="cube"/> During this season, Morandini was named 41st out of the top 50 prospects in [[Major League Baseball]] by [[Baseball America]].<ref name="cube"/> The move to second base improved his fielding percentage greatly; Morandini cut his errors in half in only one season, posting 11 with Scranton/Wilkes-Barre.<ref name="brefminors"/> He also earned a short promotion to the major league club; he played in 25 games, hitting 4 doubles and 1 home run in 87 [[plate appearance]]s.<ref name="cube"/>

==Major league career==
===1990<U+2013>1997: Philadelphia Phillies===
After a short stint in Scranton to start 1991, Morandini returned to the major leagues for the remainder of his career. He amassed four triples and thirteen stolen bases in his first full season, highlighting his speed.<ref name="bref">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/moranmi01.shtml|title=Mickey Morandini Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> The following season produced one of the most memorable moments of Morandini's career. In a game against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] on September 20, 1992, he turned an [[unassisted triple play]].<ref name="utp1">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/feats/feats8.shtml|title=Unassisted Triple Plays by Baseball Almanac|publisher=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref><ref name="utp2">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/lists/unassistedtp.shtml|title=Unassisted Triple Plays|publisher=The Baseball Cube|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> in the sixth inning, Morandini caught a [[line drive]] off of the bat of [[Jeff King (baseball)|Jeff King]], touched [[second base]] to put out [[Andy Van Slyke]], and tagged out [[Barry Bonds]] coming from [[first base]];<ref name="watn">{{cite web|url=http://philadelphia.phillies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080820&content_id=3338192&vkey=news_phi&fext=.jsp&c_id=phi|title=Where are they now? Mickey Morandini|last=Horan|first=Kevin|date=2008-08-21|work=Phillies.MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> the Pirates went on to win the game, 3&ndash;2, in [[extra innings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1992/B09200PIT1992.htm|title=Pittsburgh Pirates 3, Philadelphia Phillies 2|publisher=Retrosheet, Inc|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> It was the first unassisted triple play since 1968, and the first in the [[National League]] since 1927.<ref name="utp1"/><ref name="utp2"/><ref name="utp3">{{cite web|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1004280/index.htm|title=Between The Lines|last=Kurkjian|first=Tim|date=1992-09-28|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=2009-05-26}}</ref> Morandini was also the first second baseman in National League history, and the first in the [[Major League Baseball schedule|regular season]], to turn an unassisted triple play;<ref name="watn"/><ref name="utp3"/> all previous occurrences were made by [[first baseman|first basemen]] or shortstops.<ref name="utp2"/> The only other second baseman to achieve the feat prior was [[Bill Wambsganss]], who turned a triple play in the [[1920 World Series]].<ref name="utp3"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1920/B10100CLE1920.htm|title=Cleveland Indians 8, Brooklyn Robins 1|publisher=Retrosheet, Inc|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref>

The Phillies appeared in the [[1993 World Series|World Series in 1993]] with Morandini at the top of the lineup; he batted second in [[manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Jim Fregosi]]'s [[Batting order (baseball)|batting order]] more often than any other position.<ref name="cube"/> During the season, he turned 48 [[double play]]s with infield partner [[Kevin Stocker]].<ref name="1993PHI">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PHI/1993.shtml|title=1993 Philadelphia Phillies Batting, Pitching, and Fielding Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> Morandini had a .247 batting average during the season, the lowest among the Phillies' starters; he was second on the team in stolen bases to [[Lenny Dykstra]], and led the team in triples with nine.<ref name="1993PHI"/> His triples total was also tied for third-best in the National League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1993-batting-leaders.shtml|title=1993 National League Batting Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-25}}</ref> In 1994, Morandini posted the highest [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage (OPS) of his career, with a .787 mark.<ref name="bref"/> He also [[Base on balls|walked]] 34 times in 316 plate appearances,<ref name="bref"/> but lost playing time to [[Mariano Duncan]], who appeared at all four [[infielder|infield positions]] throughout the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/PHI/1994.shtml|title=1994 Philadelphia Phillies Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> 1995 was arguably Morandini's finest season; he batted .283 with 6 home runs, 7 triples, and 49 RBI.<ref name="bref"/> He was also named to the [[1995 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1995 All-Star team]]; he appeared in the game, going 0-for-1,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ALS/ALS199507110.shtml|title=July 11, 1995 All Star Game Play-by-Play and Box Score|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref> and was one of five Phillies to be selected for the team.<ref name="watn"/>

Morandini racked up the highest stolen base total of his career in 1996, with 26, though it was a down year for him statistically. His batting average was .250, with 3 home runs, 6 triples, and 24 doubles. He struck out 87 times while walking 49, and amassed 135 hits in 606 plate appearances.<ref name="bref"/> The following year, his batting average was at its highest point during his career as a Phillie; Morandini hit .295 and [[Slugging percentage|slugged]] .380.<ref name="cube"/> He posted a fielding percentage of .990, making only 6 errors while recording 87 double plays;<ref name="field">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/moranmi01-field.shtml|title=Mickey Morandini Fielding Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-25}}</ref> Morandini's defense throughout his career earned him the nickname "Dandy Little Glove Man".<ref name="field"/> After the 1997 season, Morandini was traded to the [[Chicago Cubs]] for outfielder [[Doug Glanville]].<ref name="bref"/>

===1998<U+2013>1999: Chicago Cubs===
In 1998, Morandini posted a .296 batting average, along with 172 hits, 8 home runs, and 53 RBI, all career highs.<ref name="bref"/> He and the Cubs also appeared in the [[1998 National League Division Series]], but lost to the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1998_NLDS1.shtml|title=1998 League Division Series - ATL vs. CHC|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-25}}</ref> Morandini made his only appearance in the [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player award]] balloting,<ref name="bref"/> tying with [[Javy L<U+00F3>pez]] for 24th in the voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1998.shtml#NLmvp|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1998 |work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=2009-05-25}}</ref>  Morandini's production declined in 1999, as he hit .241 and scored 60 runs, and he chose free agency after the season, signing with the [[Washington Nationals|Montr<U+00E9>al Expos]] in January 2000.<ref name="bref"/>

===2000: Last season and retirement===
Two months after signing with Montr<U+00E9>al, the Phillies purchased his rights from the Expos, and he returned to Philadelphia for the 2000 season.<ref name="bref"/> After batting .252 and hitting four triples for the Phillies, they traded him to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] in August for [[Rob Ducey]].<ref name="bref"/> Morandini played his final two months in the [[American League]], batting at the bottom of the order for the Jays.<ref name="cube"/> He had 29 hits in 107 at-bats, good for a .271 average, and stole a base.<ref name="cube"/>

==After baseball==
Morandini currently resides in [[Chesterton, Indiana]], where he was the head baseball coach at [[Valparaiso High School]]<ref name="watn"/> until accepting the manager's position for the [[Williamsport Crosscutters]], one of the Phillies' A-level affiliates, for the 2011 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/sports/baseball/article_b43824da-dfe1-5538-af54-195fd0817246.html|title=Mickey Morandini resigns at Valpo for job with Phillies|last=Peters|first=Jim|date=November 18, 2010|work=Northwest Indiana Times|accessdate=November 19, 2010}}</ref> He also owns and runs RSVP, a stationery store, with his wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/articles/2005/07/09/sports/top_sports/b0c46e1a2cf4bd8086257034007ad746.txt|title=It's in the cards|last=Castle|first=George|date=2005-07-09|publisher=The Times Media Company|accessdate=2009-05-24}}</ref>

